[normal]Q16 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe:[bold] Welcome. Good afternoon and thank you for the written evidence that we have had, which is interesting. One of the problems that I have in trying to get to the heart of this issue is the terminology in the field of unemployment, which to an outsider can be somewhat ambiguous. What do you think is meant by youth unemployment as opposed to worklessness and the other category of NEET that is increasingly used throughout the whole of Europe as well as the 
[normal]UK
[normal]? For example, if a young person has left school with no job and is then put by a government programme on to a short-term training scheme, where do they crop up in these figures? What are the real figures and how do we get a better understanding about the real unemployed?
[normal]Professor Maguire[bold]: You have picked up on a very key issue. If we are famous for anything in 
[normal]Britain
[normal], we are famous for defining the term NEET. We created the term and it was created in the late 1990s following concern about the growing number of young people whose destination was unknown. Prior to 1988, all young people in 
[normal]England
[normal] were eligible for income support or unemployment benefit when they left school. That was terminated in 1988, so 16 to 18
[normal] 
[normal]year-olds were no longer classified as unemployed. The only group of young unemployed that we had were the post-18 group and they were young people who were claiming benefit and actively seeking work. We had this group of young people who were operating under the radar and who had no official connection to any agency. Towards the end of the 1990s there was growing concern about this unknown group and who they were and, more critically, how many there were. Their official status was zero in the unemployment camp because they were not classified as unemployed. So we coined the term NEET
[normal]—
[normal]not in education, employment or training
[normal]—
[normal]to get a handle on this population of under-18s who were not participating in education, employment or training. 
[normal]The distinction is very much, in my mind, that the under-18s were NEET and the over-18s were those who could claim benefit and were actively seeking work. Those two definitions have become rather blurred and the NEET definition is used now more widely to incorporate both young people who are actively seeking work, the unemployed, and the non-active group, the NEET group. Within that NEET group, we now have over a million young people in 
[normal]England
[normal]. 
[normal]W
[normal]e have these strange definitions and terms, but if we want a classification of just unemployed, they are the young people who are actively seeking work and are claiming benefit. The NEET group are far more difficult to quantify in number and purpose.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Just for clarification, the NEET group, as you now describe them, do not get benefit. They could be looking for work, of course.
[normal]Professor Maguire[bold]: Of course they could, yes. The unemployed are a sub-group of the NEET group. We have half a million in 
[normal]England
[normal] who are unemployed and the rest are classified as inactive. We have “actively seeking” but that is a much more accurate count because they are counted in the unemployment statistics.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] They are registered in the 
[normal]j
[normal]obcentres and so on?
[normal]Professor Maguire[bold]: They would be registered in the 
[normal]j
[normal]obcentres and within the labour force survey. When the labour force survey is conducted, they declare themselves as actively seeking work. The inactive group are far more difficult and the problem of quantifying them is greatest within the 16 to 18 group because they have no natural entitlement to income support until the age of 18.
[normal]Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe:[bold] Do you think it is important from society’s viewpoint that we should find some mechanism whereby we can stick with them and know of their existence, where they are, what they are doing? Has anybody done any academic work to try to follow a cohort of them for a number of years to assess their cost to society or to themselves in terms of health, perhaps criminality or other areas of social problems that might arise from being in that category? I 
[normal]do not wish
[normal] to blame anybody in any sense, because a lot of people have problems that lead to the difficulties they encounter, but I wonder whether we follow through what the true cost is when we start talking about them not having anything at all from the state when in fact they are costing the state a lot.
[normal]Professor Maguire[bold]: The figures for the unknown group were very small
[normal],
[normal] but over the last couple of years they are rocketing because the infrastructure has been withdrawn to map the NEET population. So we have a growing problem with the unknown group and who they are or what they are. We cannot assume that they are NEET
[normal],
[normal] but we do not actually know who they are. 
[normal]S
[normal]ome work 
[normal]was 
[normal]done a couple of years ago by the 
[normal]University
[normal] of 
[normal]York
[normal] and the 
[normal]National 
[normal]Audit Office looking at the cost to society of being NEET, so the costs of being NEET have been quantified.
[normal]Q17 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe:[bold] Do you have any ideas about 
[normal]whether it would 
[normal]be right that we should try to track them, as we could prior to 1988?
[normal]Professor Maguire[bold]: I think it is crucial that we track them
[normal],
[normal] because if we lose young people and they have a destination unknown at the age of 16, we know from the figures that they emerge at the age of 18, having been lost for two years. They turn up at 18 because they can claim benefit and in our eyes they have been left for two years with nothing to do. The problem is far greater to fix if you have left someone for two years, or perhaps longer, than if there is instant intervention at 16 and they are supported and tracked and monitored through the system. We have disturbing numbers of unknown. I have some figures with me that show that the unknown figures since 2010 have doubled or trebled in some areas.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Would it be possible for you to send them to us?
[normal]Professor Maguire[bold]: I will send the figures to you.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Thank you very much. Prof
[normal]essor Sloman, would you like to 
[normal]add to that?
[normal]Professor Sloman[bold]: Can I defer first to Dr Copeland? I think 
[normal]this 
[normal]is a little more 
[normal]in 
[normal]his area
[normal]. I will 
[normal]then I come back, if I 
[normal]may
[normal].
[normal]Dr Copeland[bold]: Here is hoping. Maybe I should mention this definition of worklessness or joblessness. This is an interesting one and is even more recent than the NEET classification. Worklessness is an EU-wide definition
[normal],
[normal] and within the literature you will see a flipping between worklessness and joblessness
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]but 
[normal]it actually means the same thing. The definition here is individuals who are working less than 16 hours a week, so these individuals are still employed albeit working part-time or below 16 hours a week. The definition of worklessness or jobless households, for example, very much features in Europe 2020, the EU’s new reform strategy and successor to the 
[normal]Lisbon
[normal] agenda, which attempts to define poverty as individuals living in jobless households and is supposed to pick up on issues of economic inactivity. 
[normal]The problem with the definition is twofold. One is that individuals are still working, albeit for 16 hours or less a week, and the second is that the definition itself picks up all economically inactive people, such as those on disability benefits and pensioners. There is a real problem with using a worklessness or joblessness definition to look at the youth unemployment problem. It does not give you an accurate picture of what is really happening out there.
[normal]Professor Sloman[bold]: Could I make some general comments first, my Lord Chair? I was very pleased to be invited here
[normal],
[normal] but perhaps I should position myself. I am basically a training manager in organisations. That is what I have come through. I have held director roles as head of training in organisations, so I have looked at this problem from a slightly different perspective 
[normal]from
[normal] the definitions. I would make two very general observations and point you in the direction of something. 
[normal]First of all, this is about the most confused area 
[normal]for 
[normal]vocabulary that it is possible to look at. The definitions of categories
[normal] 
[normal]seem to vary. Y
[normal]ou cannot tie them down, and there are multiple schemes and acronyms, all with strange-sounding names. My view is that you have to define the problem before you can comment on the solution. The challenge facing us is
[normal] whether 
[normal]the problem 
[normal]is 
[normal]one of youth inactivity, a problem of a lost generation, or a problem of a lack of skills for the future through training
[normal].
[normal] Those are quite different problems
[normal],
[normal] but we need to determine which of those we want. With the metrics reporting and definition, it is more important to start with the problem than 
[normal]to 
[normal]try to drill down through definitions. 
[normal]Something that attracted my attention when I was looking at this problem was a Local Government Association report called 
[normal]Hidden Talents
[normal]. 
[normal]T
[normal]hat argued, very powerfully, for a scorecard for local areas, if you could agree a scorecard, because you have three 
[normal]government departments
[normal], Education, Business, Innovation and Skills
[normal],
[normal] and DWP, each producing different figures and definitions and each focusing on different areas. I fear that is not an answer to your question but I hope it is an observation that might help the Committee.
[normal]Q18 [bold]&#xa0; 
