[normal]Professor Maguire[bold]: I think there are two causes of youth unemployment. It is either down to structural changes or a labour queue hypothesis. Structural changes to the youth labour market were most dramatic in this country in the late 1980s
[normal] and 
[normal]1990s when the manufacturing sector diminished
[normal],
[normal] and therefore the traditional youth labour market that existed for school leavers was decimated. That damage to the youth labour market has never been repaired because that infrastructure does not exist. 
[normal]A
[normal]fter that 
[normal]we went towards 
[normal]encouraging increasing numbers of young people to remain in full
[normal]-
[normal]time education as an alternative to finding work. I think we are picking up the consequences of those policies now. 
[normal]We are talking about a broad spectrum of 16 to 24
[normal] year-olds
[normal], including graduates and young people
[normal],
[normal] who are leaving learning without basically literacy and numeracy, so we cannot group them all together. They have very specific needs and very different skill levels. I think we have to be quite honest here and say that we have not had a real commitment to placing young people in employment for many years, particularly the younger groups. The focus has been on increasing rates in 
[normal]full-time
[normal] learning
[normal],
[normal] and it is only when young people have emerged from that and that has coincided with a recession that we are suddenly screaming about youth unemployment. I think we have to be honest and say that that has not been a policy priority in this country and in many other countries, unlike 
[normal]Germany
[normal], which has 
[normal]always sustained a healthy apprenticeship programme that is well supported and as such ha
[normal]s
